description.plain:
Lauren Michelle Jauregui Morgado (born June 27, 1996), known simply as Lauren Jauregui, is an American singer-songwriter from Miami, Florida. She is a former member of the girl group Fifth Harmony.

Lauren​ is of Cuban descent from her parents, Michael Jauregui and Clara Morgado. She has also two siblings, Taylor and Chris Jauregui. Throughout her school years, Jauregui expressed herself through the arts, while she enjoyed constantly creating, singing, writing, dancing, choreographing, playing piano, and painting. She cites Lauryn Hill, Alicia Keys, Christina Aguilera, Amy Winehouse and Frank Ocean as her main influences.

In 2012, at the age of 15, Lauren auditioned for The X Factor performing the song “If I Ain’t Got You” by Alicia Keys. She was given four “yes” and allowed to move on into the competition. Eventually, she, along with Ally Brooke, Camila Cabello, Dinah Jane, and Normani Kordei were put into a group, later named Fifth Harmony. The group released successful singles, with “Work From Home” peaking at #4 on the Billboard Hot 100, their highest peak on the chart. The band lasted almost six years before they announced an indefinite hiatus on March 19, 2018.

When asked about her solo career, post-Fifth Harmony, the Miami native said that she’s influenced by many genres including 90’s R&B, electronica, pop, rock ‘n roll, alt-rock, and Latin music; and that she aims to perspectives on social issues and encouraging her fans to do their own work. Furthermore, Lauren has said of her songwriting:

My art is just self-explorative. I’m gonna talk about whatever it is that I’m going through, so if what I went through, I went through with a girl, you’re gonna hear about it from that perspective. If what I went through, I did with a man, you’re gonna hear it from that perspective, ‘cause I just love souls.

Her solo collaborations while with Fifth Harmony include “Back to Me” with electronic duo Marian Hill, released in December 2016 (Lauren’s first feature outside Fifth Harmony as a co-writer and vocalist); “Strangers,” a track from Halsey’s sophomore album hopeless fountain kingdom, released in June 2017; “In Your Phone,” a track from Ty Dolla $ign’s album Beach House 3; and “All Night” with Steve Aoki, released in November 2017.

On October 24, 2018, Lauren Jauregui released her debut solo single “Expectations.” Her second single, “More Than That,” was released on January 11, 2019. Additionally, Jauregui featured alongside Drew Love on clear eyes‘ debut solo song, “Let Me Know” in December 2019, and she appeared on the soundtrack of the Birds of Prey movie with the song “Invisible Chains” in February 2020. The same month, she collaborated with Puerto Rican producer Tainy on “NADA” featuring C. Tangana, and “Lento” in March 2020. It is followed by “50ft.” in April 2020.

On November 5, 2021, Jauregui finally released her long-awaited debut solo project, Prelude, via her own label Attunement Records. It includes October 2021 tracks “Colors” and “Scattered” featuring rapper VIC MENSA and November 2021 track “On Guard” featuring 6LACK. Additionally, it is accompanied by a live stream performance via Moment House.

After various projects in 2022, including the most emotional and raw ballad the singer has released since the start of her career “Always Love,” Lauren Jauregui released “Trust Issues” in March 2023. These last two singles are taken from her second EP, In Between, released on May 26, 2023.

description.plain:
‘'Expectations’‘ is one of the three songs that premiered on Jauregui’s support slot on Halsey’s 2018 Hopeless Fountain Kingdom Tour in Latin America. It had its official release on the 24th of October later the same year.

The song describes a relationship in which the other person does not appear to care about their significant other as much as the other does. ‘'Expectations’‘ expresses the struggle of wanting to change the situation, but being unable to do so. According to Lauren, it was an easy song to write and record. In an interview to MTV, she revealed that she wrote Expectations in 30 minutes.

description.plain:
“Lento” is the third solo single by singer-songwriter Lauren Jauregui, following the successful releases of “Expectations”, “More Than That”, “Let Me Know”, and “NADA” (respectively).

Jauregui reunited with Tainy, who produced her new single.

On “Lento,” which translates to “Slowly,” Jauregui encourages just that in the face of a negative lover. The song is an alluring, mid-tempo dance moment from Jauregui that shows off her smoky vocals.

description.plain:
“More Than That” is the second solo single by singer-songwriter Lauren Jauregui. She first performed this track at MTV Elections Afterparty. The song was released on January 11, 2019, and the music video one week later.  In a livestream on Instagram, Lauren revealed that she wrote “More Than That” about 2 or 3 years ago. The song isn’t necessarily based on a real story though.

Backed by 808-tinged production from Murda Beatz & Charlie Handsome, the track finds Lauren singing to admiring onlookers that they have to “come stronger than this liquor” and “be more convincing” if they “wanna take [her] home”.

description.plain:
Following her highly anticipated return with “Lento” in March 2020, Lauren Jauregui unveiled “50ft” a month later, a song about ode to self-love and protection.

Lauren sang the song for the first time prior to its release during a livestream for Billboard on March 25, 2020. Then, the Miami native shared a snippet of the unreleased track on Instagram in October 2019.

Additionally, Lauren revealed on he Instagram that she wrote “50ft.” back in 2018 “from a space of reflection on how [she] interact with the world energetically,” she then continued:

This artwork truly encapsulates the feeling of distance spoken about in the song while asserting the closeness of my relationship to my loved ones (pictured with me are my mom and sister💕) who hold me the fuck down always and forever in the midst of it all.

Accompanied by a compelling music video dedicated to her family and friends, Lauren celebrates being able to be with those she loves under one roof.

description.plain:
Lauren Jauregui ushered in a new era with “Colors,” taken from her debut solo EP Prelude. Written and produced with her friend Johnny Rain in her apartment, this single is the first as an independent artist under her label Attunement Records in partnership with AWAL.

Opening with an airy piano before sinking into R&B-style drums, “Colors” is a contemplative and emotionally charged song, revealing Lauren’s inner reality. In an October 2021 interview with Bustle, the 25-year-old singer-songwriter explained that the song is about “the shit that we all go through on a daily basis as humans: anxiety, depression, imposter syndrome, not feeling like you’re good enough, [and] unworthiness.”

Additionally, Lauren added that “Colors” wasn’t the lead single from Prelude, but rather a “thesis statement” giving a first taste of what’s coming.

songs.title: Trust Issues

description.plain:
“Trust Issues” is “an ode to potential lovers,” and serves as the second single from Lauren Jauregui’s second EP, In Between. The singer performed the song on several occasions, before releasing it on March 31, 2023.

“Trust Issues” shows Jauregui not wanting to be in a relationship due to being hurt and heartbroken by a former lover. Even though her new love interest is different, she hasn’t healed yet and doesn’t want to put the new person in what could be a toxic relationship. In a March 2023 interview with Rolling Stone, the American singer stated:

I wrote [“Trust Issues”] at a point in my life where I wasn’t healed enough to be getting into a new relationship seriously, so “Trust Issues” is a warning.

In addition, the accompanying music video is about breaking the fourth wall, and letting go of vulnerability.

songs.title: Burning

description.plain:
First performed at the New York Pride in June, 2019, “Burning” marks the first time Lauren has written and performed a track about being with a woman.

In 2017, Lauren featured on Halsey’s single “Strangers”, which depicts two female characters reflecting on their fleeting relationship. The track marked the first time either artist had released a song with female pronouns.

“Burning” has Lauren contemplating over her attraction to a woman as same-sex attraction is deemed a sin to some religions and beliefs. She uses fire metaphors to represent both her desire and her punishment of being a sinner.

Jeremy Lloyd, from the duo Marian Hill, confirmed he produced the song in a tweet. The duo had worked together before, when Lauren featured in the Marian Hill song “Back to Me”.

description.plain: Pretending was first leaked on December 26th 2024. On the song Jauregui sings about how the current state of her personal life or the world, or even both of these, make her feel miserable and how because of her celebrity status she just has to pretend everything is fine and keep going with a smile on her face.
